headline: Google Joins Singapore’s Green Fuel Tests Ahead of Flight Levy
summary: A total of nine firms plan to join the voluntary trial to purchase SAF through the Singapore Sustainable Aviation Fuel Company Ltd., or SAFCo, an entity being established under plans to begin charging a world-first green levy on departing flights from October.  The tests will allow SAFCo to refine operational, commercial and accounting processes required to meet an initial plan for flights from Singapore to use 1% sustainable fuel, the Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore said Monday in a statement.

headline: Trump to Launch $12 Billion Critical Mineral Stockpile to Blunt Reliance on China
summary: The venture — dubbed Project Vault — is set to marry $1.67 billion in private capital with a $10 billion loan from the US Export-Import Bank to procure and store the minerals for automakers, tech firms and other manufacturers.  The effort is akin to the nation’s existing emergency oil stockpile.  The stockpile is expected to include both rare earths and critical minerals as well as other strategically important elements that are subject to volatile prices.

headline: The $3 Trillion AI Data Center Build-Out Becomes All-Consuming For Debt Markets
summary: Not even the world’s biggest technology companies—not Amazon.com, not Microsoft or Meta Platforms—are prepared to foot the bill with only their own cash.  The massive equity investments in private companies such as OpenAI and Anthropic don’t come close to this Industrial Revolution-size cost.  “The numbers are like nothing any of us who have been in this business for 25 years have seen,” says Matt McQueen, who oversees global credit, securitized products and municipal banking and markets at Bank of America Corp. “You have to turn over all avenues to make this work.”

content.title: The $3 Trillion AI Data Center Build-Out Becomes All-Consuming For Debt Markets
content.summary: Not even the world’s biggest technology companies—not Amazon.com, not Microsoft or Meta Platforms—are prepared to foot the bill with only their own cash.  The massive equity investments in private companies such as OpenAI and Anthropic don’t come close to this Industrial Revolution-size cost.  “The numbers are like nothing any of us who have been in this business for 25 years have seen,” says Matt McQueen, who oversees global credit, securitized products and municipal banking and markets at Bank of America Corp. “You have to turn over all avenues to make this work.”

headline: Nvidia Stock Drops. Why Its $100 Billion OpenAI Investment Is in Question.
summary: Nvidia  stock was falling early Monday amid questions about the chip maker’s commitment for a major investment in ChatGPT-developer OpenAI.  Nvidia shares were down 1.3% at $188.75 in premarket trading.  The focus is on Nvidia’s relationship with OpenAI.
